Helping students at Bosco Jomo who don’t usually get a chance to learn has taught me the value of giving time to others. Even though I go only once a week, the hour and a half I spend with them is very meaningful. To make learning fun, I create small games and read long essays with them, which keeps both them and me motivated. I started this activity this year, and it shows me how eager they are to learn as they share how hard it is to live away from their parents. This experience has not only made me more thankful for the opportunities my parents have given me, but also inspired me to pursue higher education and share my own school experiences with others. It has motivated me to study computer science and one day organize ICT programs for students without access to resources. After tutoring, we play basketball together. I’ve played for three years and especially enjoy organizing zone games where everyone tries different positions, learning patience and teamwork. My spiritual school and the support from my community inspire me to approach all these activities with care, love, and dedication.
  
